<div class="container">
    <h1>Client-Side in Web Communication</h1>
    <p><strong>Client-side</strong> refers to operations that are performed in the user's browser rather than on the server. This is where the interface is rendered, and dynamic behavior is handled using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.</p>

    <h2>Main Responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Rendering UI:</strong> Display HTML, CSS, and images so the user can interact with the page.</li>
        <li><strong>Interactivity:</strong> Handle user actions like clicks, input validation, animations, and dynamic updates.</li>
        <li><strong>Sending Requests:</strong> Make HTTP requests to the server asynchronously using technologies like AJAX or Fetch API.</li>
        <li><strong>Processing Data:</strong> Parse and display data received from the server (usually JSON).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Updating Content via JavaScript</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Client-Side Script</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-html">
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
            <title>Client-Side Example</title>
</head>
<body>
            <h1 id="message">Hello!</h1>
            <button onclick="updateMessage()">Click Me</button>

            <script>
                function updateMessage() {
                    document.getElementById("message").innerText = "You clicked the button!";
                }
                </script>
</body>
</html>
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>In this example, all processing happens on the client side: the browser updates the message without contacting the server.</p>

